class Solution {
public:
    void helper(int idx,vector<int>& nums,vector<int> ds,vector<vector<int>>& res)
    {
        //base case
        if(idx == nums.size())
        {
            res.push_back(ds);
            return;
        }

        //include case
        ds.push_back(nums[idx]);
        helper(idx+1,nums,ds,res);
        ds.pop_back();

        //exclude case
        helper(idx+1,nums,ds,res);
    }
    vector<vector<int>> subsets(vector<int>& nums) 
    {
        vector<vector<int>> res;
        vector<int> ds;
        helper(0,nums,ds,res);
        return res;
    }
};

Subsets – Backtracking Approach
Maintain temporary list ds and result res.
Call recursive helper(idx, nums, ds, res) starting from idx = 0.
In helper:
If idx == nums.size() → push ds to res → return
Include current element → push nums[idx] to ds → recurse helper(idx+1) → pop (backtrack)
Exclude current element → recurse helper(idx+1)

Time: O(2^N × N) → all subsets × copying each subset
Space: O(N) → recursion stack + temporary list

One-liner: “Generate all subsets via include/exclude recursion; exponential time, linear space per recursion depth.”
